post_text:
Covid-19 Bus Information
The basic plan of the Eastern Lancaster County School District on Covid-19 and transportation will be one of reasonable precautions. We share this information now so you can make a personal decision as to whether or not you want to participate in the school operated transportation program. Below are key considerations.

We are building the routes and loading the buses normally.
Because buses will be scheduled to capacity all learners will be required to wear masks the entire ride, unless there is a medical excuse.
We are working with our bus contractor on aggressive disinfection protocols, but we cannot guarantee that buses will be disinfected between every single run.
We will be constantly ventilating buses with partially open windows throughout the year, learners will need to plan ahead in cooler months.
Afternoon drop off times may vary do to changes in the bus dismissal procedures from the parking lots.
We hope that these few points help you make an educated decision on how you may prefer to get your learners to and from school.

Today is School Lunch Hero Day! Since the ELANCO School District buildings have closed, our amazing food service department has served over 60,000 meals to community families. They are outside serving nutritious food to our families every Tuesday from 10am-1pm at GSHS. Please help us HONOR and CELEBRATE them!

A special thank you to our local community business’: Grocery Outlet for donating grocery bags, Yoder's Country Market New Holland for letting us borrow shopping carts, B & G Paper Products for all those last minute disposables we need and CrossNet Ministries for their continued partnership!

Grassland FFA is selling freezer quarts of pulled pork again this year to benefit an agricultural non-profit in our Whole Hog Event. The quarts are $15 dollars each. The pork is cooked, pulled and packaged all between Saturday and Monday this weekend. There is no sauce or seasoning used and each quart of pulled pork is packed full.

See Mrs. Ranck and/or Mrs. Peirson in the Ag Department for any further information!

shared_text:
Garden Spot Village
March 4 at 5:02 PM ·

Recently, Eastern Lancaster County School District middle school students used the technology in their 3-D lab to create and produce products, such as a soda-can opener, to help solve various problems Garden Spot Village residents face. To reciprocate the relationship, 13 residents visited the lab today to see what it had to offer and interact with the students. It was a great learning experience for everyone to see how technology and manufacturing can happen in the classroom. #community #collaboration #purpose

post_text:
Driver’s License Testing Available at the Lancaster County CTC!
Can’t schedule a Class C Driver’s Test for months? Don’t want to wait? Call the Lancaster County Career & Technology Center’s Driver License Testing Center. The Testing Center is located at the Brownstown Campus, 231 Snyder Road, Ephrata and is open Monday through Friday from 8:30 am to 4:30 pm. The Driver Test that the LCCTC offers is the same as the standard PennDOT test. For more information on fees and scheduling, please contact the Testing Center at 717-859-5102.

The Driver Test that the LCCTC offers is the same as the standard PennDOT test. For more information on fees and scheduling, please contact the Testing Center at 717-859-5102.

At the October Board meeting, Garden Spot High School Principal, Mr. Matthew Sanger, presented to the Board and recognize our October Students of the Month.

Amanda Hoover was nominated as one of garden Spot's Students of the Month.

Amanda is the daughter of Michelle and Aaron Hoover of Mohnton, PA. Amanda is enrolled in several honors courses including Honors Algebra II, Honors American History, Honors English, Honors Geometry, Honors Chemistry. Amanda plays field hockey and softball and participates in GSPA stage crew. Amanda spends her time volunteering as a camp counselor, going on mission trips and working on her family farm. Amanda hopes to have a career in criminal justice or human services after graduating.

post_text: The MS counselors took 18 learners in both 7th and 8th grade to Construction Wars, an interactive field trip at ABC Keystone in Manheim. Volunteers from companies specializing in carpentry, electric, HVAC, plumbing and other construction careers were on-hand to guide students through interactive stations. The volunteers shared important information about their industry and the skills deficit they are seeing first hand in their careers. Learners walked away with their projects, including a stool and a tool carrier, as well as their hard hats and vests. It was an amazing hands-on experience!

Volunteers from companies specializing in carpentry, electric, HVAC, plumbing and other construction careers were on-hand to guide students through interactive stations. The volunteers shared important information about their industry and the skills deficit they are seeing first hand in their careers. Learners walked away with their projects, including a stool and a tool carrier, as well as their hard hats and vests. It was an amazing hands-on experience!

post_text: The Mobile Ag Ed Science Lab was formed by the boroughs to promote Agriculture Science under the department of Ag. There are 8 labs across the state of Pennsylvania. The kids do PSSA science objectives that are all farm based; for example, making glue out of milk, crayons out of soy beans, and even extracting DNA out of bananas. In today's lesson, the 6th graders at Brecknock Elementary School read a story about tree farmers, and talked about the importance of trees and then made 'Tree Bracelets'.

post_text:
The Garden Spot chapter of the National Honor Society had many accomplishments during the 2018-2019 school year. The annual meeting with the returning college freshmen helped current members to learn what to expect in the first year of college. To benefit the school district, NHS members volunteered at events such as the High School “Challenge of the Classes” and “Spring Fling”, as well as in “Read Across America” in the elementary schools. The club also held a blood drive that collected 43 pints of blood for the community.

In addition to these events, all 75 members volunteered 20+ hours of their time and spent nearly 1,200 hours serving the community during the school year. Congratulations to the NHS Students and Advisors on a great school year of service.
text:
The Garden Spot chapter of the National Honor Society had many accomplishments during the 2018-2019 school year. The annual meeting with the returning college freshmen helped current members to learn what to expect in the first year of college. To benefit the school district, NHS members volunteered at events such as the High School “Challenge of the Classes” and “Spring Fling”, as well as in “Read Across America” in the elementary schools. The club also held a blood drive that collected 43 pints of blood for the community.

In addition to these events, all 75 members volunteered 20+ hours of their time and spent nearly 1,200 hours serving the community during the school year. Congratulations to the NHS Students and Advisors on a great school year of service.

The ELANCO Annual Bee Impactful Teacher Award

The ELANCO Annual "Bee Impactful" Teacher Award
April 8, 2019 at 12:17 PM ·

We are now accepting nominations for the 4th Annual "Bee Impactful" Teacher Award!

This award is to honor teachers that go above and beyond to have a tremendous impact on their students. One teacher will be selected by a committee from the pool of nominations and will receive a $2,500 award.

Students, alumni, parents and ELANCO staff can nominate a deserving teacher. To submit a nomination, please complete the online form at http://www.beeimpactful.com.

post_text: Last week, a group of Garden Spot Middle School Students attended “Construction Wars” at ABC Construction in Manheim. More than 40 volunteers from the construction industry spent the day with our students to give them hands-on experience with carpentry, electrical wiring, PVC plumbing, and sheet metal. Students also learned about the educational paths to these high skilled, high wage, and high demand jobs.

post_text: Today, Second Grade learners at Brecknock presented a History Museum to the school community as a culmination of their History module. There were over 15 exhibits on display!

post_text:
On Wednesday, March 6th, Garden Spot Middle School welcomed the YES! Program from Junior Achievement. Students in 7th and 8th grade experienced “Your Economic Success” which connected the importance of their education to their future economic and career success. It was the initial year for this program and the Elanco SD would like to thank the 40 community volunteers who made it a wonderful learning experience.

Local businesses partners plus numerous parent volunteers worked hard to help our students discover the choices that lie ahead. Small student groups traveled through six stations intended to help students gain an appreciation for the importance that career and financial decisions will play in their lives as young adults. It was interactive and fun for all involved and provided meaningful conversation about career exploration.

post_text:
Garden Spot High School Students will be going on an educational, service-learning trip to Vietnam in June 2019. The group is partnering with a local Vietnam veteran and businessman, Marlin King, to raise funds toward purchasing wheelchairs to distribute while in Vietnam.

On the evening of February 2nd, a fundraiser is being held at Our Lady of Lourdes Church in New Holland. The evening includes a casual, catered dinner that includes lasagna/vegetarian baked ziti, salad, bread, Vietnamese appetizers, and dessert followed by a short presentation by Mr. King on his ongoing project of delivering wheelchairs to disabled people in Vietnam who cannot afford them.

For more information and to register, please see the flyer and visit https://www.eventbrite.com/e/gshs-senior-project-vietnam-2019-tickets-53640504192

On Saturday, October 13th, from 9 am – 2 pm, Garden Spot High School is hosting a Buick Drive for Students Event. Buick will donate $10 to the school for each valid test drive up to 100 test drives. If the event exceeds 100 test drives, Buick will double their donation to $20 per valid test drive, for a maximum donation of $10,000!

There are two restrictions: 1.) Drivers must be 21 years of age or older with a valid driver’s license and proof of insurance; and, 2.) Limit two (2) donations per household.

Come out to take a test drive to help raise funds for GSHS student clubs and activities

post_text: Today, Monday, May 21st, the entire ELANCO School District is participating in our own Mini Relay for Life to raise funds and awareness for the fight against cancer. The student and faculty members of the ELANCO Health Council have been working hard to make sure all buildings in the district are a part of this great event. Every student and staff member will have the opportunity to walk for 30 minutes in honor or memory of someone who has been impacted by cancer. The event kicked off this morning at Garden Spot and will spread to each of the elementary schools later in the day.

On the afternoon of May 3rd, Garden Spot High School Students had the opportunity to witness a mock vehicle crash simulation put on by members of the New Holland Police Department, local fire companies, and EMS. Several of our own Garden Spot Performing Art actors and actresses played the role of crash victims. A MedEvac helicopter even made an appearance.

The goal of the simulation was to display the dangers and real-life consequences of driving under the influence and driving while distracted.

http://blog.elanco.org/hs/2018/05/03/mock-dui-crash-simulation/

Local businesses will have a list of internship opportunities available along with a short description of the possible job duties.

For more information and to see a list of internship partners who will be attending, visit - http://blog.elanco.org/pathways2success/about-internship/internship-fair/

Thanks to our local business partners for attending this event.

post_text: Blue Ball 5th graders display their learning of Economics and Entrepreneurship by holding a "Food Truck Expo" where they displayed their food truck ideas and business plans. Their food truck concepts included use of PA agriculture products. Their business plan presentations included an introduction to the business, a logo design, a description or theme of the business, target audience, a financial plan, and an advertising/marketing plan. Amazing job 5th grade!
